<HEADLINE>
FT  14 SEP 92 / Foreign Exchanges and Money Markets: Cut and rally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DEALING in all the major currencies will be affected by the extent of
today's cut in the Bundesbank's official interest rates, writes James Blitz.
If the Germans had not pledged to cut their official rates, the unilateral
devaluation of the Italian lira could have led to a run on sterling and
other weaker currencies in the exchange rate mechanism this morning.
However, the Bundesbank's promise to cut its official rates for the first
time since 1988 could trigger a rally for the dollar and sterling in
European trading today.
Early operations in Australia and New Zealand showed how wild markets could
be today. In New Zealand, the dollar surged as high as DM1.51, after opening
in New York on Friday at DM1.4503. Sterling was at a high of DM2.81, two
pfennigs above its close in London. The French franc was trading as low as
FFr3.2923 against the D-Mark, having been at around FFr3.40 for the last few
weeks.
Even if the Germans cut rates, however, the outcome of Sunday's referendum
on Maastricht could still create tensions for European currencies. France
must hope that a cut in German rates will be followed by a cut in French
rates and that this will increase the Yes vote on Sunday. If it does not,
trading next Monday could be no less intense.
The day will also bring the first test of whether devaluation can save the
Italian lira from further interest rate rises. The experience of Finland is
that devaluation, far from stopping the rot, only brings more pressures on
the currency. Some dealers think that a 7 per cent devaluation is far too
small, and that the lira was already overvalued against the D-Mark by around
15 per cent until last night.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
