<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 92 / Cabinet resistance to EC post for Kinnock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PLAN for Mr Neil Kinnock, the former Labour leader, to take over as
Britain's second EC commissioner in Brussels has run into unexpected
opposition within the cabinet.
Mr John Smith, the present opposition leader, has informally proposed to Mr
John Major that Mr Kinnock be appointed to the high-profile post. He would
replace Mr Bruce Millan as Labour's nominee to work alongside Sir Leon
Brittan, the senior British commissioner.
Traditionally the prime minister would automatically accept Mr Smith's
recommendation, but ministers said last night that it had caused serious
concern about the potential impact on the Tory back benches.
Some ministers are questioning whether the proposed appointment would
encourage more Tory MPs to rebel against Mr Major's support for Maastricht.
Their fears underline the sensitivity in the highest ranks of the government
over Europe.
It is understood that Mr Kinnock discussed a possible move with Mr Major
just before the summer break. Mr Kinnock left with the impression that the
prime minister was ready to endorse his appointment. Mr Millan has said he
is ready to stand down at the end of this year in favour of the former
Labour leader.
But during a discussion at Thursday's cabinet meeting some ministers raised
the possibility that Mr Kinnock's nomination to such an influential post
could inflame passions among Tory MPs about the Maastricht treaty on
European union. No firm proposal was put to the cabinet.
Last night senior Labour officials indicated that Mr Smith would not
formally propose Mr Kinnock until it was clear that Mr Major would endorse
his appointment. But the view of one senior minister was that, with the
dispute in the open, the prime minister would have to move quickly to
resolve the issue.
Labour unrest, Page 4
</TEXT>
