FT  12 SEP 92 / Breath-test driver wins appeal
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A MOTORIST yesterday made legal history when his conviction for failing to
provide a breath specimen was quashed because of a legal loophole.
It was thought that more than 100,000 other drivers with similar convictions
in England and Wales going back almost 25 years could now apply for them to
be overturned.
Mr Kofi Gandaa, aged 41, a computer engineer of Camberwell, south-east
London, had been found guilty of failing to provide a breath specimen.
He had been convicted under Section 7(6) of the 1988 Road Traffic Act by Bow
Street magistrates in London.
His counsel, Mr Donal McGuire, said section 7(6) of the act was 'bad for
duplicity'. It created two offences of failing to provide a specimen and
there were different penalties for each.
