<HEADLINE>
FT  12 SEP 92 / Bush's F-15 ploy clouds BAe Saudi deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM, DAVID WHITE and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush yesterday flew to the electorally important state of
Missouri, to tell workers at the McDonnell Douglas plant in St Louis that he
was authorising the sale of 72 F-15 fighters to Saudi Arabia. The
announcement threw a question mark over whether Saudi Arabia intends to
proceed with purchasing more Tornado strike aircraft from Britain.
A long-awaited deal, estimated at Pounds 4bn, for 48 Tornados and British
Aerospace Hawk light fighters and trainers, is believed to have been
awaiting signature since August.
BAe maintains its prospective deal will be unaffected by Saudi purchases
from the US.
Mr Bush had already hinted that he was likely to approve the sale, but chose
to turn the formal announcement into a rally for his election campaign, as
he did last week when he reversed his policy on arms sales to Taiwan by
approving the sale of F-16 fighters built by General Dynamics in Texas.
Missouri, though it has fewer electoral votes than Texas, is similarly
viewed as critical to Mr Bush's chances of winning re-election. The Dollars
9bn sale is expected to provide 40,000 jobs and affect the economies of 45
states.
Although Israel and its supporters in the US have in the past objected to
the sale of F-15s to Saudi Arabia, administration officials say they do not
expect strong opposition from the Israeli government.
Saudi Arabia initially opted for the Anglo-German-Italian Tornado in the
mid-1980s when it was barred from purchasing the F-15E, the two-seat,
long-range strike version of the US jet.
It renewed its request for F-15Es in 1989 and again last year, after the
Gulf war, asking for 48 of the strike version and 24 two-seat
air-superiority fighters.
The White House said the Saudis would get F-16XP models, less capable than
the F-15E, which is only flown by the US Air Force.
McDonnell Douglas has been anxious that Congress should notified within the
next few days in order to obtain approval this year.
Although Mr Bill Clinton, the Democratic presidential candidate, has given
qualified backing for the sale, the next opportunity for congressional
approval would not be expected to arise before the spring.
The US State Department yesterday announced its decision to waive
restrictions on the export of six satellite projects to China, Reuter
reports. They include the APSAT, Asiasat 2, Intelsat VIIA, STARSAT,
Afriastar and Dong Fang Hong 3 satellite projects.
</TEXT>
