<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / MoD seeks hovercraft bids
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MINISTRY of Defence plans to revive the use of hovercraft after
abandoning them in the 1980s.
It is inviting tenders for up to four diesel-engined hovercraft to start
service with the Royal Marines by the end of next year.
Main UK contenders for the contract, expected to be worth about Pounds 1m,
are Griffon Hovercraft, which has recently clinched export deals for Sweden
and Thailand, and Slingsby Aviation.
Among others invited to bid is an Australian company, Airlift Marine. Five
French companies are also due to be notified.
The US and Russia make significant use of hovercraft for amphibious
operations. The UK set up an inter-service trials unit in the 1960s, but the
gas-turbine craft of the time were found to be too unreliable, noisy and
expensive.
The MoD said modern technology had largely overcome those drawbacks.
The planned craft, much smaller than the US marines' tank-carrying Landing
Craft Air Cushion, will carry up to 16 fully equipped men or two tonnes of
stores over sea, land or ice at up to 30 knots.
Conventional landing craft will still be needed to transport vehicles, heavy
equipment and the main body of troops ashore.
</TEXT>
