<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / Banks urged to balance goals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR BRIAN PEARSE, chief executive of Midland Bank, warned yesterday that
banks and companies should take care to balance the pursuit of rewards for
shareholders against other goals.
'The relentless focus on financial performance places a high value on the
pursuit of shareholder value as the dominating factor in business
management,' he said, in a seminar for the Chartered Institute of Bankers.
He warned of 'dangers if shareholder value is over-accentuated - for example
if short-term decisions are taken that are not in the customer's best
interest'.
There has been a debate between banks and their shareholders over the past
few years about whether banks have been run with sufficient emphasis on
rewarding shareholders. Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, governor of the Bank of
England, warned recently that banks should put the interests of shareholders
and customers above the public interest.
Mr Pearse insisted yesterday that there was nothing to distinguish a bank's
obligations to its shareholders from those of any other limited company.
He said that a bank had 'moral and social obligations' to take account of
its relationships with 'suppliers, staff, customers and the community'.
Mr Pearse added: 'There will be times in the business cycle when the
long-term fulfilment of strategic aims requires short-term profit sacrifices
while investment or restructuring is undertaken.' So a bank's policy of
increasing dividend payments to shareholders may 'need to be reviewed' when
profits are under pressure.
UK banks have been reluctant to cut dividends. Midland's dividend cut after
its poor 1990 financial results was the first by a UK clearing bank since
the 1930s.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
