<DOCNO>FT923-3484</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIKCNAEWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920911
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / International Company News: Dutch insurer ready to launch
bid for BBL
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL and ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMSTERDAM, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONALE Nederlanden Group (ING), the big Dutch banking and insurance
group, said yesterday it was prepared to launch a bid for Banque Bruxelles
Lambert (BBL). The offer would value Belgium's second largest bank at
BFr63.6bn (Dollars 2.18bn).
The bid would be part of ING's campaign to create a second 'home' market,
but the outcome depends to an extent on the attitude of Groupe Bruxelles
Lambert, the Belgian holding company which controls 24 per cent of BBL.
GBL is reserving judgment on the offer until a formal bid is launched, but
Comte Jean-Pierre de Launoit, GBL's deputy chairman and a BBL director, said
yesterday: 'The price (BFr3,600 a share) doesn't seem satisfactory.'
As a first step, ING, which already owns slightly more than 10 per cent of
BBL, is seeking to buy a 6.72 per cent stake held by Unipar and SBH
Investments of Italy. If these and other conditions are met, ING said it
would launch a bid for the rest of the Belgian bank's shares sometime after
mid-October. The offer would be conditional on ING securing at least 51 per
cent of BBL's share capital. The two moves could cost ING up to Fl 3.2bn
(Dollars 2bn) in cash, to be raised in part by an issue of preference
shares.
The Banking Commission, Belgium's takeover authority, recommended the Dutch
company should launch a full bid if it bought the Italian stake. It is the
first time ING has made clear it intends to acquire a majority holding in
BBL following months of wrangling between BBL's various institutional
shareholders about future alliances.
BBL's management favours an international alliance, but others - who may
include Mr Albert Frere, GBL's influential chairman - have pressed for links
with a Belgian institution, such as Credit Communal.
ING's proposals have split the BBL board. At Wednesday's emergency meeting,
directors appointed by GBL, Royale Belge and Winterthur - Belgian and Swiss
insurance companies - were out-voted when they opposed plans to allow ING to
look at the bank's books. They argued it could be dangerous to give the
Dutch group access to confidential information, in case it decided not to
bid. The board said it would decide whether to support a bid once it had
examined the terms of an offer.
Under a syndicate deal among BBL's main institutional shareholders, any
shares must first be offered to GBL, which has a 15-day right to first
refusal. GBL is almost certain to turn down the shares, if it lifts its
stake it will be forced to bid for the whole group.
Unipar has offered its shares to the syndicate members for BFr3,600 each,
against BBL's closing price on Wednesday of BFr3,275.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
