<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / International Company News: Management team may buy Spanish
store chain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MANAGEMENT team has emerged as the most likely buyer of Galerias
Preciados, the Spanish department store chain owned by Mountleigh, the UK
property group in receivership.
The buy-out team, led by the Galerias's financial director, the chief
planning executive and the head of its legal department, is believed to have
reached an underwriting agreement with Caja Madrid, a leading savings bank,
.
Peat Marwick, the receiver, said 'several offers' had been received for
Galerias and there would be 'no fire sale'. A decision is expected in 'weeks
rather than days'.
Mr Michael Babcock, Galerias' general manager, who was appointed by
Mountleigh in February last year, resigned last week and was replaced by Mr
Jaime Uya, a former head of Galerias' marketing division, who is understood
to favour the management buy-out.
The withdrawal of a bid made jointly by Parques Urbanos, a leading developer
of shopping centres in Spain, and by Zara, a domestic textile manufacturer
and retailer, has also stirred speculation of a management buy-out.
Mr Carlos Bardon, chairman of Aserinvest, a Madrid consultancy that advised
the joint bid, said the offer had been withdrawn because Peat Marwick failed
to provide details of an audit on Galerias within the time specified by the
bid.
A feature of the management buy-out offer is that it would be endorsed by
unions representing Galerias' 8,000 employees. The unions have staged
several protests recently, to press for a quick sale and the security of
their jobs.
It is understood that should the managers win control of Galerias, it was
likely at least two stores could be subsequently acquired by Marks and
Spencer, the UK retailing group which is operating in Madrid and Seville and
is seeking to expand further in Spain.
</TEXT>
