<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / International Company News: Rhone-Poulenc surprises with
profits warning
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RHONE-POULENC, the French state-owned chemical group, surprised the Paris
market yesterday when it warned it would not achieve its operating profits
target for the third quarter this year. The group's prefered investment
certificates fell 13 per cent from FFr600 to FFr530 on the news.
Analysts said the warning, after assurances four weeks ago that the target
was achievable, had undermined Rhone-Poulenc's credibility, effectively
scuppering short-term possibilities of privatisation or changes in capital
structure.
The company, France's largest chemicals group, estimated growth in the third
quarter of between 10 and 15 per cent. In February, Mr Jean-Rene Fourtou,
chief executive, promised that in spite of recession, earnings growth in
1992 and 1993 would be at least 20 per cent.
The group said it had not been aware of the full extent of the shortfall
until after its half-year results in August. One analyst said this suggested
either a sudden downturn, or the company's reporting systems needed
improvement.
The company blamed several factors for the under-performance, but stressed
the weakness of the US dollar. It said although its US healthcare operations
reached its targets, the dollar's depreciation below FFr4.80 had affected
results of its US businesses.
Last year about 23 per cent of Rhone-Poulenc's turnover was in the US. Its
US operations made trading profits of about FFr1.2bn (Dollars 240m) against
group profits of FFr6.2bn.
The dollar's depreciation also hit the group's organic chemical
intermediates operations. The relative strength of the franc made its
products increasingly uncompetitive in America, while cheap US imports were
undermining prices in European markets.
Rhone-Poulenc net income rose 38 per cent to FFr1.55bn in the first half
from FFr1.12bn in the same period last year.
</TEXT>
