<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / Bout of face-saving strikes Ulster talks: The significance
of the Democratic Unionists' walkout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE and Our Belfast Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Democratic Unionist party reaffirmed yesterday that it would take no
further part in talks on the future of Northern Ireland until the Irish
government's constitutional claim over the province was on the negotiating
table.
The walkout comes as the talks reach a crucial point. After months of
preparatory meetings and preliminary skirmishing, the core issues - the
Irish Republic's constitutional claim to Northern Ireland and whether the
unionists will accept some all-island dimension to an agreed solution - are
about to be discussed at the talks.
The DUP's withdrawal has cast a shadow over the entire talks process. A
plenary session went ahead yesterday without the party.
The Ulster Unionist party made clear that it would not be joining the DUP in
withdrawing from the process, but would continue in discussions 'with the
aim of forcing the Irish government to withdraw its legal claim to the
territory of our part of the United Kingdom'.
A meeting between the British and Irish governments is scheduled to take
place in London today.
The apparent impasse in the talks appears to have much to do with the art of
face-saving. Any agreement will require concessions from the four political
parties and the two governments involved, but all know that a concession
made too soon, or too readily, might bring a backlash from their political
constituencies, not to mention the paramilitaries, and maybe the end of a
political career or two.
The week after next, the talks are due to move from Stormont, the seat of
government in Northern Ireland, to Dublin. It will be a symbolic moment, and
one of great sensitivity for hardline unionists such as the Rev Ian Paisley,
the DUP leader, who have consistently cold-shouldered their southern
neighbours.
Determination to maintain the confidential nature of the talks has caused
difficulties with some rank-and-file unionists who feel they are not being
kept sufficiently appraised of developments. Some DUP members resigned when
Mr Paisley agreed to sit at the same table as Dublin ministers.
So when the constitutional issue was placed fourth of a four-item agenda at
this week's talks, the DUP apparently felt it was time to spell out more
clearly its attitude to the Irish constitutional claim.
The fact that Mr Paisley and his deputy, Mr Peter Robinson, left two
delegates keeping their seats warm at the table - one of them Mr Paisley's
daughter Rhonda - strengthens the view that the fuss may be little more than
playing to the loyalist gallery.
Once the item is reached on the agenda, the two leaders have hinted that
they will be back at the table, but probably only if that point can be
reached next week, before the talks move to Dublin.
There is little indication yet that Dublin is prepared to meet Mr Paisley's
demand on the constitutional issue without something in return from the
unionists. The unionists have given no indication publicly or, it seems,
within the negotiations, of what reciprocal step they might take.
The Irish government insists that its territorial claim is up for
negotiation, but also that 'nothing is agreed until everything is agreed'.
To make unilateral concessions to the unionists before their arrival in
Dublin would be very difficult politically.
Few doubt that the Fianna Fail-led coalition would be able to deliver a
constitutional change as long the unionists and the British government can
make real concessions to protect the interests of the minority community in
Northern Ireland.
The constitutional change that Mr Paisley is seeking would seem to be within
his reach, but he is also under pressure to reveal some of his own
negotiating cards at the table.
The art of face-saving requires that he does so without appearing to have
done so.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT923-3526</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CIKCNADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920911
</DATE>
