<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / Public expenditure committee shapes up for spending battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's public expenditure committee will meet for the first time
next week, although the occasion is expected to be largely procedural.
The Treasury has yet to decide whether spending ministers should be invited
to attend to make their cases - as they were under the 'star chamber'
arrangements - or whether they should simply submit papers.
Bilateral discussions between spending ministers and Mr Michael Portillo,
the chief secretary, will still be continuing when the committee meets, so
the results of those discussions will wait until the second meeting, which
is scheduled for the beginning of October.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, will chair the committee, whose membership
the Treasury had originally hoped could be confined to 'trusties' - Treasury
ministers or ministers with very small departmental budgets.
However, Mr John Major insisted the spending ministers should be represented
by Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, and Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and
industry secretary. The committee will submit options to the cabinet, which
will decide on fund allocation between departments.
Increases in the public-sector borrowing requirement are to be limited by
linking spending to the expected low economic growth in the next few years.
The cabinet has agreed that for 1993-94 the government should keep to the
planning total of Pounds 244.5bn announced last November.
