<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / BR faces complaint of abuse of power
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHARTERAIL, the private freight train operator, which is on the brink of
financial collapse, has lodged a formal complaint with the European
Commission alleging an abuse of monopoly power by British Rail.
The complaint has been made under Article 86 of the Treaty of Rome which
prohibits abuse of a dominant market position and which can lead to fines
and action in national courts.
Charterail ceased operations at the end of last month when it ran out of
money. It said BR was to blame for charging too much for the locomotives and
crew that hauled Charterail's freight trains over BR's tracks.
The company says the rates charged were consistently higher than indicative
prices quoted by BR when Charterail was formed. They also failed to fall as
road haulage rates did.
Last night Mr Robin Gisby, Charterail's managing director, said there were
two main grounds for the company's complaint to the EC. He alleged that in
some instances BR had refused to quote rates for new traffic, and in others
had not quoted fair prices based on an objective view of their costs.
Charterail's complaint appears to be aimed at putting pressure on BR to
negotiate a new set of lower rates that will enable the company to go back
into business.
Mr Gisby said Charterail had succeeded in finding investors who were
prepared to plug the company's funding gap if a viable business could be
re-established.
'The missing element is the new rate structure from BR,' he said. 'We are
waiting to hear from BR on what basis they are prepared to restart the
operation of our trains. If it is on the same basis as it was two or three
weeks, ago, the numbers will clearly not add up.'
In that event, Mr Gisby said that the company would go into liquidation.
Charterail's complaint to the EC is doubly embarrassing for BR because the
corporation is a 22 per cent shareholder in the company. The rest is owned
by a range of private-sector interests led by GKN, the industrial group.
BR said it would look at any new proposals from Charterail, but its
rail-freight operations were unsubsidised and it was under an obligation to
cover its costs.
Mr Jimmy Knapp, general secretary of the RMT transport union, yesterday
predicted that two more InterCity routes - between Plymouth and Penzance and
Crewe and Holyhead - would be cut.
He also told delegates at the TUC Congress that privatisation was not
inevitable. 'Rail privatisation will be the poll tax of this parliament,' he
said.
</TEXT>
