FT  11 SEP 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One's heart scarcely lifts at the thought of yet another police series, but
the opening episode of Between The Lines last week was extremely impressive.
Perhaps the time is ripe for a series which looks specifically at those
internal units intended to police the police themselves, in this instance
London's CIB: Complaints Investigation Bureau. In today's episode (9.30
BBC1) policemen shoot dead an armed man who is trying to force his way into
his girl friend's flat and are accused of operating a 'shoot to kill'
policy.
Rumour has it that Paul Merton is planning to have a night's sleep some time
in 1996. Meanwhile he continues to participate in every series which has any
connection with new comedy. He is credited as co-writer on C4's new vehicle
for Julian Clary, Terry And Julian (10.30), which is followed by a repeat of
Paul Merton: The Series (11.00).
The Fall Of The House Of Usher (12.10 BBC1) is that rarity, a rather good
horror movie. It remains fairly faithful to the book, stars Vincent Price at
the top of his form in 1960, and achieves an effective atmosphere without
straining to terrify the life out of you as today's shockers do.
