<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / BMA will not fight London hospitals axe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT proposals to close some of London's most famous hospitals will
not be obstructed by the British Medical Association even though many
doctors' jobs will disappear.
At a meeting this week with Dr Brian Mawhinney, health minister, BMA leaders
accepted the case for hospital closures and concentrated on trying to ensure
that they take place in a planned and orderly way.
A report by Sir Bernard Tomlinson, former chairman of the Northern Regional
Health Authority, on hospital provision in London is due to reach the
government by the end of next month.
With Sir Bernard's deadline for completing his study approaching,
speculation is mounting over which hospitals might close. A report in the
London Evening Standard yesterday said that the Tomlinson report would lead
to the disappearance of St Thomas', St Bartholomew's, Charing Cross and the
combined University College-Middlesex hospitals in their present form.
Mr John Chawner, chairman of the BMA consultants committee, said the
association recognised that there had to be change in London hospital
provision. 'It has to be properly managed and planned around a sensible
timetable.'
The big London teaching hospitals are in increasing financial difficulty now
that, under the government's health reforms introduced last year, health
authorities outside the capital have greater incentives to treat patients
locally. In addition, Mr Chawner said, they were experiencing 'planning
blight' as a result of the Tomlinson inquiry. Health authorities were
reluctant to place contracts with a hospital that might be earmarked for
closure.
Doctors in London estimate that between 600 and 700 consultant posts, plus
the jobs of numerous other junior medical staff, are likely to disappear as
a result of the Tomlinson rationalisation.
Plans to close famous London hospitals are certain to meet opposition from
their staff, but BMA leaders will not back individual hospital campaigns.
They will concentrate their energies on issues arising out of the closures.
Those include:
Opening up opportunities in other parts of the country for medical staff who
lose their jobs in London.
Protecting the future of specialist clinical and research units housed in
teaching hospitals selected for closure.
Ensuring that the surviving hospitals contain a proper balance of services
to meet the needs of the capital.
The position adopted by the BMA even before the Tomlinson report has been
published shows the extent to which the new financial structure of the
government's health reforms has undermined the London teaching hospitals.
London has proportionately more hospital beds than the rest of the country.
Mr Chawner said the government had recognised decisions could not be based
on the failure of particular hospital managers to balance their books, and
had to be properly planned.
</TEXT>
