<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / Row over return of EETPU avoided
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Trades Union Congress yesterday cleared the way for readmission of the
EETPU electricians' union, which is now a section of the merged AEEU
engineering workers' and electricians' union.
Delegates accepted a formula that allows considerable room for manoeuvre in
affiliation talks. A damaging row over the the union's reaffiliation was
avoided when the NUJ journalists' union agreed not to table a motion which
might have led to the AEU engineering workers' union, the EETPU's partner in
the new AEEU, quitting the TUC.
Nonetheless, Mr Colin Bourne, an NUJ delegate, was given one of the warmest
receptions of the week-long conference when he made a speech that included
strong criticism of the EETPU.
He accused the electricians of trying to build an alternative to the TUC and
basing it on 'every tiny scab union they could lay their hands on'. The
electricians would be welcomed back only if the issues that 'have made them
such pariahs are resolved to the satisfaction of the members of the club
they seek to join'.
The NUJ's motion would have imposed tough conditions on the talks, requiring
the EETPU to give up members it has recruited from other unions.
The debate was watched from the visitors' gallery by Mr Paul Gallagher,
EETPU general secretary. Afterwards he said he was not surprised at the
strength of feeling shown in the debate. But in areas where it matters
'people have forgiven and forgotten'.
He said the EETPU would obey TUC rules if it rejoined.
</TEXT>
