<HEADLINE>
FT  11 SEP 92 / Vietnam may lift investment curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY MCDERMOTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VIETNAM is considering liberalising its foreign investment law, according to
Professor Nguyen Mai, vice-president of the State Council for Co-operation
and Investment.
He told a conference in London yesterday the proposed changes included:
allowing foreign investors to lease land for up to 50 years instead of 20;
permitting the sale of shares in some state enterprises to foreigners -
thereby creating a new category of foreign investment;
giving preference to joint venture investments, spread around the country.
Mr Mai said he had brought to London a list of 548 projects for investors to
consider.
There were 416 joint-venture projects in operation at the end of August,
involving capital investment of Dollars 3.35bn, for which Dollars 1.69bn has
been raised.
The main foreign partners, Mr Mai said, came from Taiwan, Hong Kong, France,
Netherlands, Japan, Britain, Australia, the Commonwealth of Independent
States, South Korea and Canada.
Of the 416 projects, 233 (with capital investment of Dollars 1.11bn) were in
industry, 18 (Dollars 900m) in oil and gas, 41 (Dollars 660m) in hotels and
tourism, and 55 (Dollars 166m) in services.
A report* issued at the conference said Vietnam could become one of
South-East Asia's most important tourism destinations if hotel building
plans were fulfilled.
It said 40 hotels had opened in Ho Chi Minh City and 40 more were to be
built.
The total number of visitors to Vietnam in 1991 was about 850,000, including
300,000 from western Europe, South-East Asia, Japan, Australia and North
America.
The figure for tourism was 36 per cent higher than in 1990 - with
indications that in 1992 the figures would grow by at least that amount
again.
*Vietnam: The Next Asian Tiger? British Consultants Bureau, 1 Westminster
Palace Gardens, 1-7 Artillery Row, London SW1P 1RJ. Pounds 265.
</TEXT>
